        " . The treaty secured a payment to Constantinople of some 42 pounds worth of gold each year. Theodoric was well educated by Constantinoples best teachers. His status made him valuable, since the Amal family from which he came , allegedly ruled half of all Goths since the third-century AD. Historian Peter Heather argues that Theodorics claims were likely self-aggrandizing propaganda and that the Amal dynasty was more limited than modern commentators presume. Until 42 Theodoric remained in Constantinople where he spent formative years catching up on all the Romanitas it had taken generations of Visigothic Balthi to acquire. Theodoric was treated with favor by the Emperor ": null
